<br>
Does that mean then that I can follow you around with a monk and just chain feign death mobs on you?<br>
<br>
I mean, you shouldnt be in the zone if you cant handle EVERY SINGLE MOB IN IT AT ONCE, right?  I think someone should use that argument in the soapbox and see how far it gets.  Fighting in a city is no different.<br>
<br>
The rules are facts and published for everyone to see.  There's no OOC disruption caused to a city by killing the inner guards, so why use an OOC mechanic to &quot;get back&quot; at those that have the audacity to want to roleplay attacking a city?<br>
<br>
Again, you speak in terms of &quot;calling the guards&quot; and it all being in-character... does that mean if my home is robbed I need to go punch a cop, have them chase me back to my house, then hide while they get the real criminals?<br>
<br>
Im sure after they are arrested, we could all have a good laugh about it, not like they would be upset I socked them in the mouth, right?<br>
<br>
You talk about pathetic, what's pathetic is CHEATING because you arent willing to go through the trouble of roleplaying with people.  NEVER have I been on a city raid where the person who was training roleplayed with the raiders.  They never say a word, they go and punch a trainer and bring it to the zone.  Great roleplay there.  Perhaps before you go pointing fingers and calling situations pathetic, you should actualy... I dont know... get involved in the situation you're speaking of.<br>
<br>
Roleplay far out weighs rules in my opinion, but there is no roleplay in having to attack a guard for them to assist you.  Every game has rules, asking that the rules be enforced evenly is not &quot;hiding behind them,&quot; it's expecting to play the game under the conditions set.<br>
<br>
Every game has rules, and the rules need to be followed.  I fail to see where that can be argued.  Are the rules not clear?  Do they not state that training is a violation of the PnP?  Because if they do... then there is no argument and no excuse.<br>
<br>
